## [3] ADVERSARIAL / FAILURE-PATH CASES

Probe D — anti-vacuity (the load-bearing half of the redesign):
  chown -R --reference=/some/ref /tank/Server/AppData/plex
  -> FAIL "parsed=[], offenders=[]".
  The OLD guard PASSES this (no colon in `--reference=/some/ref` -> no match ->
  no offender -> green). The new guard reddens on parsing NOTHING — which is
  precisely how the predecessor stayed green. Confirms the fail-safe direction.

Probe E — fail_msg `| int` is load-bearing and guarded:
  stripped to `{{ plex_idmap_base + plex_uid }}` -> fail_msg check FAILS
  (uid=False gid=False). Restored byte-exact: tasks/main.yml sha256 6f2dd7ba.

Secondary (a) BEHAVIOUR verified, not just shape — rendered the real fail_msg
arithmetic through ansible-core 2.21.1's bundled Jinja2 3.1.6:
  plex_uid=999 (int, shipped default): PRE-FIX ok / POST-FIX ok  -> happy path
                                        unchanged; the fix is not a behaviour
                                        change on the path that already worked.
  plex_uid="999" (string, `-e` override): PRE-FIX CRASH
      TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'int' and 'str'
                                          POST-FIX RENDER OK -> "chown -R 100999"
  Confirms the Bug Fixer's claim verbatim: the crash fired on the ONLY path that
  renders fail_msg (the failing-ownership path) — i.e. exactly when the operator
  needs the chown — and the coercion fixes it.

Secondary (b) verified against LIVE /etc/pve/lxc/110.conf:
  g 0 100000 44 / g 44 44 1 / g 45 100045 948 / g 993 993 1 / g 994 100994 64542
  u 0 100000 65536
  The defaults comment now matches this byte-for-byte. Arithmetic re-derived:
  tile `g 45 100045 948` covers in-CT gids [45,992]; 991 -> 100045+(991-45)
  = 100991 == flat 100000+991 -> the +100000 shift holds for 991 ONLY via that
  tile. Punched 44/993 map 1:1 (flat shift would wrongly say 100044/100993).
  The comment's scoping (uid map IS a single tile; gid map is NOT) is CORRECT.

